6. Initialize & build the model. Identify the points of improvement and implement the same¶

In [16]:
model3 = Sequential()

activation = ['relu', 'tanh', 'sigmoid', 'hard_sigmoid', 'linear','softmax', 'softplus', 'softsign']
learning_rate = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3]
loss = ['mean_squared_error','binary_crossentropy','mean_squared_logarithmic_error','mean_absolute_error','hinge','squared_hinge']

result = {}

for i in activation:
    for j in learning_rate:
        for k in loss:
            model3.add(Dense(200, kernel_initializer='uniform',activation = i))
            model3.add(Dense(10, kernel_initializer='uniform',activation = i))
            model3.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='uniform',activation = i))
            optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(j)
            model3.compile(loss = k,
            optimizer=optimizer ,  metrics=['accuracy'])
            epochs = 10
            history = model3.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=epochs, validation_split = 0.2, verbose = False)
            hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
            hist['epoch'] = history.epoch
            print('For ',i,j,k)
            results = model3.evaluate(X_test, y_test.values)
            result[i] = results
print(result)

7. Predict the results using 0.5 as a threshold¶

In [ ]:
# As was mentioned in the project forum: 

        # The default threshold for model.predict() in sklearn is 0.5.

        # So, you can comment in the submission notebook.
In [ ]:
# so best accuracy and least loss (loss: 0.0784 - accuracy: 0.7945) were achieved with below model hyper-parameters:
        # Activation function = sigmoid
        # Learning_rate = 0.001
        # Loss = mean_squared_logarithmic_error
In [ ]:
# building a new model using those parameters
In [17]:
model_final = Sequential()
model_final.add(Dense(200, kernel_initializer='uniform',activation = 'sigmoid'))
model_final.add(Dense(10, kernel_initializer='uniform',activation = 'sigmoid'))
model_final.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='uniform',activation = 'sigmoid'))
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(0.001)
model_final.compile(loss = 'mean_squared_logarithmic_error', optimizer=optimizer ,  metrics = ['mae' , 'mse'])#change metric to plot
epochs = 500 # changed to have even higher accuracy
history = model_final.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=epochs, validation_split = 0.2, verbose = False)
hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
hist['epoch'] = history.epoch
results = model_final.evaluate(X_test, y_test.values)
